  "editorial": {
    "headline": "Yankees Pummel White Sox in Fifth to Seize First Place",
    "subheadline": "CWS 5, NYY 10. Top of the division changes hands — or firms up.",
    "lead_angle": "The New York Yankees seized first place Wednesday night, pummeling the visiting Chicago White Sox with a five-run fifth inning that broke open a tight ballgame. The final was 10-5. Yankee Stadium watched its team respond just two innings after coughing up an early lead, a rally that cemented Carlos Rodón’s victory. The loss was hung on Anthony Kay, who couldn't escape the fifth-inning deluge. For the Yankees, the win was a statement in a series with heavy division implications.\n\nChicago had taken its only lead in the third, a short-lived 3-2 advantage built on the first of two Colson Montgomery home runs. The Bronx was quiet until the bottom of the fifth. The Yankees sent nine men to the plate, turning the game on its head against a flagging Kay. The inning was a blur of singles and walks, capped by a two-run knock from José Caballero that chased Kay from the mound and put New York ahead for good.\n\nEven in defeat, Colson Montgomery was the most dangerous man on the field. The White Sox shortstop finished 2-for-4, accounting for four of his team’s five runs with a pair of towering home runs. His solo shot in the ninth was a final, futile gesture. While Montgomery did his part, his teammates could not solve Rodón or the Yankee bullpen. The loss drops Chicago out of the top spot in the American League Central, a position they’ll have to fight to reclaim tomorrow.",
    "reason": "Two division leaders, one winner — the standings implications make this the marquee matchup."
  },
